statement:
Prove that the complete set of triples \((x, y, z)\) of positive integers that satisfy the system of congruences
\[
\begin{cases}
xy \equiv 2 \pmod{z}\\
yz \equiv 2 \pmod{x}\\
zx \equiv 2 \pmod{y}
\end{cases}
\]
is \(\{(2, 2, 2), (2, 3, 4), (2, 6, 10), (3, 8, 22), (3, 10, 14), (4, 5, 18), (4, 6, 11), (5, 4, 18), (6, 14, 82), (6, 22, 26), (1, 2, 2k) \mid k \geq 1\}\).

Prove that the only functions $f : \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}$ that satisfy the functional equation $f(f(n)) + f(n+1) = 2n + 3$ and the inequality $f(n) \geq n - 1$ for all $n \in \mathbb{Z}$ are given by \(f(n) = \begin{cases} 
n + 4 & \text{if } n \equiv 0 \pmod{5} \\
n - 1 & \text{if } n \not\equiv 0 \pmod{5}
\end{cases}\).

Prove that the remainder when the number $N$ of ordered 2011 - tuples of positive integers $(a_1, a_2, \ldots, a_{2011})$ with $1 \le a_1, a_2, \ldots, a_{2011} \le 2011^2$ such that there exists a polynomial $f$ of degree $4019$ satisfying the following conditions:
1. $f(n)$ is an integer for every integer $n$;
2. $2011^2 \mid f(i) - a_i$ for $i = 1, 2, \ldots, 2011$;
3. $2011^2 \mid f(n + 2011) - f(n)$ for every integer $n$;
is divided by $1000$ is equal to $211$.

Prove that the functions $f: \mathbb{Z} \rightarrow \mathbb{Z}$ that satisfy the equation $f(m+n) + f(m-n) = 2f(m)f(n)$ for all integers $m$ and $n$ are given by \(f(n) = \begin{cases} 
1 & \text{if } n \equiv 0 \pmod{4} \\
0 & \text{if } n \equiv 1 \pmod{4} \\
-1 & \text{if } n \equiv 2 \pmod{4} \\
0 & \text{if } n \equiv 3 \pmod{4}
\end{cases}\).

Prove that the Dirichlet function, defined as
\[f(x) =
\begin{cases}
1 & \text{for } x \in [0, 1] \setminus \mathbb{Q}\\
0 & \text{for } x \in [0, 1] \cap \mathbb{Q}
\end{cases}
\]
is Lebesgue integrable on the interval \([0, 1]\) and that its Lebesgue integral over \([0, 1]\) is equal to \(1\).

Prove that the Dirichlet function, defined as
\[f(x) =
\begin{cases}
1 & \text{for } x \in [0, 1] \setminus \mathbb{Q}\\
0 & \text{for } x \in [0, 1] \cap \mathbb{Q}
\end{cases}
\]
is Lebesgue integrable on the interval \([0, 1]\) and that its Lebesgue integral over \([0, 1]\) is \(0\).

Prove that there exist infinitely many pairs of distinct prime numbers $(p, q)$ that satisfy the following system of congruences:
$$
\begin{cases}
2^{p - 1} \equiv 1 \pmod{q} \\
2^{q - 1} \equiv 1 \pmod{p}
\end{cases}
$$

