statement:
Let $\{A_1, \dots, A_n\}$ and $\{B_1, \dots, B_n\}$ be sets of points in the plane. Suppose that for all points $x$ in the plane, the following inequality holds:
$$\sum_{k = 1}^{n}D(x, A_k) \ge \sum_{k = 1}^{n}D(x, B_k)$$
where $D(x, y)$ denotes the Euclidean distance between points $x$ and $y$. Prove that
\begin{align*}
\sum_{k=1}^n a_{kx} &= \sum_{k=1}^n b_{kx} \\
\sum_{k=1}^n a_{ky} &= \sum_{k=1}^n b_{ky}
\end{align*}
where $A_k=(a_{kx}, a_{ky})$ and $B_k=(b_{kx}, b_{ky})$ for $k = 1,\cdots,n$, which means the sets $\{A_1, \dots, A_n\}$ and $\{B_1, \dots, B_n\}$ have the same center of mass.

Prove that the functions \(f: \mathbb{Z} \rightarrow \mathbb{Z}\) that satisfy the functional equation \(f(x + 1 - f(xy + 1)) = f(x)f(1 - y)\) for all integers \(x, y \in \mathbb{Z}\) are \(f(x) = 0\), \(f(x) = 1\), \(f(x) = x\), and \(f(x) = \begin{cases} 
x & \text{if } n \mid (x - 1) \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}\).

Prove that there does not exist a polynomial \(P(x) \in \mathbb{R}[x]\) with \(\deg P \ge 1\) such that:
a) \(P(x) \in \mathbb{Q}\) for all irrational \(x\);
b) \(P(x)\) is an irrational number for all \(x \in \mathbb{Q}\).

Prove that if \(f:\mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}\) is a function that satisfies the following conditions for all integers \(x\):
\begin{align*}
f(x + 4)-f(x)&=8x + 20,\\
f(x^{2}-1)&=(f(x)-x)^{2}+x^{2}-2,
\end{align*}
then the ordered pair \((f(0), f(1))\) is either \((0, 0)\) or \((0, 2)\).

Consider the system of linear equations given by

\[
\begin{matrix}
a_{11}x_{1} + \ldots + a_{1q}x_{q} = 0, \\
a_{21}x_{1} + \ldots + a_{2q}x_{q} = 0, \\
\ldots, \\
a_{p1}x_{1} + \ldots + a_{pq}x_{q} = 0,
\end{matrix}
\]

where $q = 2p$ and each coefficient $a_{ij}$ is an element of the set $\{-1, 0, 1\}$. Prove that there exists a solution $(x_{1}, \ldots, x_{q})$ for the system with the following properties:

a) All $x_{j}$, for $j = 1, \ldots, q$, are integers;

b) There exists at least one $j$ such that $x_{j} \neq 0$;

c) $|x_{j}| \leq q$ for any $j = 1, \ldots, q$.

Prove that there exists an $n_0 \in \mathbb{N}$ such that for all $m \geq n_0$, there exist three positive integers $a$, $b$, and $c$ satisfying the following conditions:

(i) $m^3 < a < b < c < (m+1)^3$;

(ii) $abc$ is the cube of an integer.

Prove that there exists an \(n_0 \in \mathbb{N}\) such that for all \(m \geq n_0\), there exist three positive integers \(a\), \(b\), and \(c\) satisfying the following conditions:

(i) \(m^3 < a < b < c < (m+1)^3\);

(ii) \(abc\) is the cube of an integer.

